helpcentre_topic: I need more information > How do I renew or borrow a third time?
helpcentre_answers:
Ready for renewal? We'll send you an email and display an invitation on your account page as soon as you repay both your loans and we pre-approve you. Keep in mind that renewing requires a new credit check, and we'll select the best membership type for you based on the results. However, we can't guarantee renewal eligibility or the specific membership you'll receive.
  
 Can I renew before my membership ends?
 Sure! Once you've repaid both loans and are pre-approved, we'll notify you via email and on your account page. If you want to renew early, check your eligibility and consider early settlement. We calculate early settlement amounts using the Consumer Credit Act guidelines to align with your credit agreement's APR. Remember, new memberships depend on eligibility and affordability checks.
  
 What if I haven't received an invite to renew?
 Hang tight! We check our existing members' eligibility monthly, so your chance may be just around the corner. Keep an eye on your account for updates.
  
 Can I get more than two advances?
 Our credit agreement allows for a maximum of two advances per term. You can request each advance at any time within the term, but one must be repaid before requesting the next. After repaying both loans, we'll contact you via email and on your account once you're eligible to renew.
  
 When can I borrow after renewing my membership?
 Once you renew, you can request your first advance right away - no need to wait 14 days like with your initial membership.
 If you're having any issue with your reapplication or have any further questions please contact us here.

helpcentre_topic: I need more information > Why am I being asked to connect to open banking?
helpcentre_answers:
Why are you asking me to connect my bank account to Creditspring?
 Connecting your bank account to Creditspring is a safe and secure way to provide essential details for your application. We use a third party, AccountScore, to connect your bank account. We will have read-only access to transaction data that we will use to evaluate your application or understand your financial situation more. Please note, this is a safe way for us to view your transactions and at no point are your access details stored on our system. 
  
 Which third party does Creditspring use for open banking?
 The provider Creditspring uses to connect your account to Open Banking is AccountScore. They are a technology company that focuses on building a more inclusive financial system for all.
  
 Is connecting my Creditspring account to AccountScore safe?
 Yes, Open Banking is designed to be very secure. This is thanks to the strict rules around how it works and how your data is kept safe with rigorously tested software and security systems. Youre also protected by data protection laws and the Financial Ombudsman Service.
 Any apps and websites that want to take part are registered on the Open Banking Directory. They're also regulated by the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA).
 Your information will only be shared if you give permission to an authorised provider. You'll also never be asked to share your password or log on details with anyone other than your own bank or building society.
  
 Why can't I find my bank?
 Though AccountScore covers many current accounts in the UK and the Republic of Ireland, there may be some financial institutions that dont support direct connections. If your institution isnt on the list please contact AccountScore via hello@equifax.com.

helpcentre_topic: I need more information > How do I unsubscribe from your mailing list?
helpcentre_answers:
How do I unsubscribe from your mailing list?
 We're sad to see you go! If you would like to unsubscribe from our mailing list, please click 'Unsubscribe' located at the bottom of any marketing email you have received. This can take up to 24 hours to update on our system. We apologise in advance if you receive an email within this time. If you are receiving other communications from us, this may be related to settings on your previous account or application. Please contact our support team directly here if you have any further queries regarding this.

helpcentre_topic: I need more information > What else should I know about memberships?
helpcentre_answers:
What types of memberships are available at Creditspring?
 We offer various memberships that will assist you in planning for your future, building your financial stability and boost your finances for unexpected expenses. There is a limit of one membership per person, and there are 12 monthly instalments
 We do things a bit differently. Instead of adding interest, wed rather give you a no-interest loan and charge a membership fee that is spread over the course of your agreement. We believe this is a simpler and honest way of doing business. It also means that as a member, you know youll never pay more than your monthly membership fee and what you borrowed.
 This leaves you with more time to plan and budget for a better financial future. This is something our customers love, with no surprises or hidden fees!
 You may be wondering if this is cheaper than borrowing on your credit card, dipping into your overdraft or getting a loan from someone else. This is where the APR figure comes in.
 The Annual Percentage Rate (APR) levels the playing field when it comes to lending, making it easier to compare different types of lending across different types of lenders. It works really well for loan terms that are a year or more because it is an annual number.
 However, If you define 'cheaper' by how much you need to pay, many people look at the total amount payable. In terms of how much you will pay, in pounds and pence, Creditspring is one of the cheapest ways to borrow 400 or 600 twice a year. Even cheaper than the average cost of the top five banks arranged overdraft charges, assuming you borrow and repay in the same way required by Creditspring.
 Our APR is higher than many because we collect our loans faster than other lenders. We do this because this is what our members asked for. Creditspring Members want to be in debt for as little time as possible. One consequence of us collecting money faster is that our APR ends up being higher, but our total charge does not change.
 By including our APR figure we are fulfilling our commitment to being as open and as transparent as possible, and we trust that our members see value in our product.
  
 Plus Membership (Rep APR 54.6%)
 There's a 12 fixed monthly membership fee. With this membership, you will have access to two no-interest, pre-approved 500 advances per year. The first advance must be paid in 6 monthly instalments before the remaining is accessible.
 Representative example: Total amount of credit 1,000 repayable over 13 months. 12 monthly membership payments of 12. Rate of interest 0% p.a. (fixed) Representative APR 54.6% The first repayment for each advance is 83.35 due 45 days after drawing, followed by 5 monthly repayments of 83.33. Total amount payable 1,144. 
  
 Core Membership (Rep APR 83.1%)
 There's a 10 fixed monthly membership fee. With this membership, you will have access to two no-interest, pre-approved 300 advances per year. The first advance must be paid in 6 monthly instalments before the remaining is accessible.
 Representative example: Total amount of credit 600 repayable over 13 months. 12 monthly membership payments of 10. Rate of interest 0% p.a. (fixed) Representative APR 83.1%. The first repayment for each advance is 50 due 45 days after drawing, followed by 5 monthly repayments of 50. Total amount payable 720. 
  
 Step Membership (Rep APR 88.8%)
 There's a 7 fixed monthly membership fee. With this membership, you will initially have access to two no-interest, pre-approved 200 advances per year. The first advance must be paid in 6 monthly instalments before the remaining is accessible.
 Representative example: Total amount of credit 400 repayable over 13 months. 12 monthly membership payments of 7. Rate of interest 0% p.a. (fixed) Representative APR 88.8% The first repayment for each advance is 33.35 due 45 days after drawing, followed by 5 monthly repayments of 33.33. Total amount payable 484. 
  
 The Stability Hub
 There is no fee for this membership. As a Stability Hub Member, you'll have exclusive access to a tool-box where you receive personalised scores, tips and resources to assist you in building your financial stability.
  
 Is there a late fee or any other fees that will be charged?
 Creditspring is committed to ensuring members are building their financial stability and enhancing their behaviour with their finances. This is why we do not charge a late fee for late payments. We trust that our members are committed to making the right decision for their future. All we ask is that you notify us as soon as possible to work out an agreement with your payment. You will need to notify customer service at least 5 business days before your scheduled payment date. We will try to get to a repayment schedule that works for us both.
 If you miss or are late in making any membership fee payments or the repayments of loans, we will report that to the Credit Reference Agencies. This can lower your credit score and severely damage your ability to access credit from other providers in the future.
  
 What are the application requirements for a Creditspring membership?
 There are many factors involved in determining if you are eligible for a Creditspring membership. The following are some of the requirements to apply for a Creditspring membership:
 You must be over the age of 18
 Have a UK bank account older than 3 months
 Earn a minimum of 14,000 per year
 Have no recent CCJ, IVAs or bankruptcies
 Creditspring membership is subject to status. Terms and conditions apply.
  
 Why do I need to pay a monthly membership fee if I have not borrowed or have paid off my advance(s)?
 As per the credit agreement signed when becoming a Creditspring member, you are required to pay a fee every month for the term of the agreement. The payment of this fee gives you access to two advances repayable over 13 months. These fees are charged irrespective of whether you make use of the advance(s) or not.
  
 What happens if I don't pay my membership fees or fail to repay any advances?
 If you miss or are late in making any of your monthly membership fee payments or the repayments of your advances, we will report that to the Credit Reference Agencies. If this payment is made within the seven day grace period after the scheduled charge date, we will not report the payment as late. 
  
 How long do I have to repay each of my advances?
 When you request your advance with Creditspring, you will be asked to specify the date you would like to repay your advance each month. Your repayment start date can be within the following 2 to 6 weeks after requesting your advance. New members will have six months to repay the loan amount for each loan.
 Please note that if you make an additional repayment (this can be done via debit card within your Creditspring account), it will reduce your remaining monthly repayment balance.
 In addition to repaying your advance, you must continue to pay your monthly membership fee as per your credit agreement with Creditspring.
  
 What is the total cost for each membership?
 Step Membership: The total cost of your full credit agreement term is 84. You will pay this at a rate of 7/month, whether you borrow or not. Each loan of 200 is repayable over 6 monthly instalments, with no interest.
 Core Membership: The total cost of your full credit agreement term is 120. You will pay this at a rate of 10/month, whether you borrow or not. Each loan of 300 is repayable over 6 monthly instalments, with no interest.
 Plus Membership: The total cost for a year is 144. You will pay this at a rate of 12/month, whether you borrow or not. Each loan of 500 is repayable over 6 monthly instalments, with no interest.
 You can cancel your membership at any time. If you have not taken any loans and would like to cancel your membership, you can do so by telling us one month in advance. We will not reimburse the fees for any of the previous months of your membership.
 If you have an outstanding loan amount or have used advance(s) but don't currently have any outstanding balance and would like to cancel your membership, please [[click here]]. In the case of early settlement, there may be an outstanding fee owe to you or to us calculated based on when you borrowed and repaid. After you've paid the settlement in full your membership will be cancelled.
  
 What forms of payment are accepted?
 For all monthly membership fee payments and advance repayments, direct debit is the only form of payment we accept. As per your credit agreement, members are required to connect their direct debit to their Creditspring account. The monthly membership fee and your advance repayment will be collected on the dates you have scheduled when becoming a member. Unfortunately, we will not be able to accept credit card payments. There are exceptions where one-off payments that are not connected to direct debit are allowed via debit. For example, overdue payments.
  
 How does Creditspring make money?
 We assist our members in building their financial stability and improving their behaviour with their finances. By making credit simpler, we can provide a financial backup plan for when you need it most. We encourage our members to take control of their finances and work towards building a plan for their future. This is why at Creditspring you are not charged interest or any fees to ensure you work towards reaching your financial goals. Our only source of revenue is the monthly membership fee that each Creditspring member pays. We make money when satisfied customers continue to pay their monthly membership fee to borrow, without stress and build their financial stability.

helpcentre_topic: I need more information > What happens if my application is rejected?
helpcentre_answers:
What happens if my application is rejected?
 Please note that when you make an application or request to renew your membership, we carry out a new credit check and so can't confirm eligibility before these checks are completed. If you're rejected, you can reapply 30 days after your last application.
 While we can't provide specific information on why an application has been rejected, we would recommend contacting a credit reference agency for further information in relation to your credit score.
  
 How do I resume my application for a Creditspring membership?
 If you have started an application for a Creditspring membership but haven't completed it, please enter your email here. You will then be sent a link to resume your application.
  
 How can I complete my application if you are not able to verify my bank information?
 Unfortunately, we will not be able to proceed with your application if your bank account cannot be verified. If you would like more information on this matter, we suggest that you contact Equifax (here), as bank accounts are verified for us by them. This is to protect customers and avoid fraud. Please note, this does not affect your credit score.
 If you would like to apply again using another bank account that is older than 3 months you can do so in a month's time.
  
 Do I need to have direct debit to become a Creditspring member?
 You will need to have an active direct debit with us in order to become a Creditspring member. Unfortunately, if your bank account does not support direct debit transactions you will not be able to become a member with Creditspring.
  
 What should I do if my address is not listed on the application form?
 If your address does not appear on the application form please contact Equifax to resolve this issue. When Equifax add your address to their database it'll also then appear in the drop-down list on our website.
  
 Why was my application not approved?
 A number of factors determine your Creditspring membership eligibility. This can include, but is not limited to, the information you provide us and the information that's on your credit file.
 If your questions haven't been answered by this article, please get in touch with the team here.

 For more details regarding our different products, please consult this article.
  
 When can I get my advance?
 Once you sign up for a membership, there is a 14 day wait period during which you can withdraw free of charge. Once the 14 days are up, your first advance will be unlocked, and you will be able to claim it at any time. All you will need to do is login to your Creditspring account and press borrow. The amount of the loans will depend on which membership you have.
  
 How can I cancel?
 You can cancel by following the process here. As part of your statutory rights, you are entitled to withdraw within 14 days of signing the Credit Agreement. If you are past the 14 days period, but have never borrowed an advance, we request your account to be up to date before cancelling. This means that membership fees will have come due, and will need to be paid before cancelling. If you have borrowed an advance, an early settlement fee may apply to ensure you pay the APR agreed at the time the credit agreement was signed.

helpcentre_topic: I need more information > What is the Spring Score?
helpcentre_answers:
What is the Spring Score?
 The Spring Score tracks your borrowing power, and shows which Creditspring product you may be eligible for.
  
 How does Creditspring calculate my Spring Score?
 Your Spring Score is calculated from a variety of sources available only to lenders. Some of the information comes from Equifax, a credit reference agency, and some comes from the financial data you share with us.
  
 How should I use my Spring Score as a paid member?
 Check your Spring Score each month to see how your borrowing power has changed. As you near renewal time, you can use your Spring Score to estimate the product you'll be eligible for next.
  
 How should I use my Spring Score as a free member?
 As you build your financial stability, using tips in the Stability Hub, you'll be able to track the changes in your Spring Score. When you become eligible for a product you'll see it reflected in your Spring Score, and we'll notify you to make sure you don't miss out.
  
 How do recommendations work?
 Your Spring Score comes with personalised recommendations to help you improve your borrowing power - and your Spring Score. These are updated each month, in line with your Spring Score.
  
 How accurate is my Spring Score?
 Your Spring Score is as accurate as the data we receive. Please make sure to report any changes in your financial situation, to ensure that your score is up-to-date.
  
 How often is my Spring Score updated?
 In line with your credit report, your Spring Score is updated each month. Check back regularly to make sure you don't miss anything!
  
 My Spring Score has gone down - how is this impacting my membership?
 If your Spring Score goes down, you may be able to borrow less when renewing your membership. Check your Spring Score to find out.
  
 My Spring Score has gone up does it mean I can upgrade my membership?
 While your membership is fixed to the terms in your agreement, you can apply for a renewal to explore any different options that may be available. Please note that all renewals are subject to affordability and eligibility checks.
  
 I was invited to apply, does it mean I'm 100% eligible?
 Pre-approval is based on a soft search - while this usually gives us a good idea of whether we could approve you, it doesnt give us the whole picture. This is why we make sure to tell you about the need for additional checks at this point. Once weve received your application and permission to do a hard check, we can find out with certainty whether we can accept your application.

helpcentre_topic: I need more information > What is the Stability Hub?
helpcentre_answers:
What is the Stability Hub?
 The Stability Hub is a free toolbox that helps Creditspring members build their credit and stay in control of their finances. Within the Stability Hub members have access to personalised scores that will give them a better understanding of their current financial situation and improve their relationship with their finances.
 The Stability Hub has offers exclusive to Creditspring members. Along with offers, the Hub has resources and tools that are regularly updated in order to assist in their journey to better their financial stability!
  
 What are the benefits of the Stability Hub?
 There are many benefits of having access to the Stability Hub. This is a great product to have if you are looking to find new resources, exclusive offers and tips to build your credit score and financial stability. The Hub is a toolbox that helps Creditspring members build their credit and stay in control of their finances. Members receive personalised score that shows a current analysis of their financial situation and their relationship with finances. Regularly updated, resources and tips are constantly evolving within The Hub. Happy Building!
 Please join the Stability Hub here.
  
 How do I cancel my Stability Hub Membership?
 If you would like to cancel your free Stability Hub membership you will need to log in to your account. From your Profile section, you can cancel your membership.
  
 Will a Stability Hub Membership affect my credit score?
 As a Stability Hub Member, it is free of charge and nothing will be reported to the credit rating agencies. You will get exclusive offers and tips to build your financial stability.
  
 How do I apply for a loan if I have a Stability Hub membership?
 Having a Stability Hub Membership grants you access to the Hub. It is designed to help members build their financial stability and improve their financial future. At the moment Stability Hub members do not receive a loan. However, we will monitor your credit improvement through the Stability Score when you're likely to be eligible for a membership with a Credit Agreement, we will invite you to apply right away!
  
 What is a CMS check?
 A CMS check is a type of check run to ensure that the data we hold on you is up to date and to let us know if you are close to being accepted for one of our products. It is not visible to any other lenders and will not impact you if you are looking for another loan or mortgage.

helpcentre_topic: I need more information > Can you help me with my direct debit mandate?
helpcentre_answers:
Why do I need an active direct debit mandate?
 As part of your credit agreement, you have agreed to pay us via direct debit. This gives our members the flexibility to control their repayments but it is a part of member's agreement with us to have an active direct debit.
 Please note that cancelling the direct debit mandate does not cancel the Credit Agreement.
 In order to cancel your membership, please follow the instructions here.
 If you have previously cancelled your direct debit mandate with your bank and wish to reinstate the mandate click here.
 Please note that late payments are required to be reported to the credit rating agencies as per their latest guidelines.
  
 Why have you set up a direct debit mandate before I signed the Credit Agreement?
 Because your Credit Agreement requires you to have an active direct debit mandate, we create one before you sign the Agreement. However, please rest assured that no payments will be planned against this mandate until the Credit Agreement is signed.
 If you have changed your mind and do not wish to complete your application, you can cancel your mandate at any time by contacting your bank.
  
 How do I reinstate my mandate?
 If you have a cancelled direct debit mandate please click here and follow the instructions.

helpcentre_topic: I need more information > How will this impact my credit rating?
helpcentre_answers:
How will this impact my credit rating?
  
 If I've never applied?
 Searching for loans on many different comparison sites involves each potential loan supplier running a 'soft' search. This is why you might have seen our company name on your credit file after using a loan comparison site even if you don't recognise our name.
 These soft searches are not visible to other prospective lenders when they assess your eligibility. If you feel that you might have been the victim of fraud or identity theft then please find more information here.
  
 Will applying affect my credit score?
 If you apply for a Creditspring membership and are not eligible, it will not affect your credit score. It will leave a soft footprint on your credit report that only you will be able to see.
 If you are eligible for a Creditspring membership and you accept a membership, our credit check will then be posted as a hard footprint on your credit report, accessible by other lenders. Once you are a member, we will continue to report your monthly membership payments and any repayments of your advances to the credit agencies.
  
 During your membership
 Do you report my payment behaviour to Credit Reference Agencies? 
 Yes, we report your payment behaviour to Credit Reference Agencies. Repaying your advance(s) and monthly membership fees on the scheduled dates outlined to you in a timely manner is considered to be good credit behaviour. This could improve your access to credit from other providers.
 Will late payments and an overdue balance affect my credit file? 
 Payments reported as missed or late can lower your credit score and severely damage your ability to access credit from other providers in the future.
 If you miss monthly membership fee payments or repayments for your advance(s), you can clear the overdue amount via debit card by logging into your Creditspring account. Unfortunately, we will not be able to accept credit card payments. If payment is made within 7 days from your scheduled repayment date, your payment will not be reported as late to the Credit Reference Agencies. Please be mindful that if you miss or are late in making any of your monthly membership fee payments or the repayments for your advance(s), we will report that to the Credit Reference Agencies. You may also be in breach of your agreement with us, which could result in the termination of your Creditspring membership.
  
 What is a CMS check?
 A CMS check is a type of check run to ensure that the data we hold on you is up to date and to let us know if you are close to being accepted for one of our products. It is not visible to any other lenders and will not impact you if you are looking for another loan or mortgage.
 If you would like to contact our team please click here.

helpcentre_topic: I need more information > When can I request an advance?
helpcentre_answers:
As a new member, how long do I have to wait to access my advance?
 Once you are approved for a Creditspring Membership you will not be able to access your first advance for 14 days. There is a 14-day wait period in place for your first advance because we want to ensure our members are building their financial stability. By taking the time to set a financial plan and by having a thought-out backup plan in place for emergencies, Creditspring is here to assist you.
  
 You can see when you will be able to borrow your first loan (if you haven't yet) here.
 After the 14 days, you'll be able to ask for your first advance whenever you want and we will transfer the funds to the bank account we have on file. Please be aware that although we aim to have your advance transferred to you immediately, it can take up to 24 hours to go through.
  
 As a renewing member, how long do I have to wait to access my advance?
 Once your renewed membership starts you will be able to immediately access your first advance. Please be aware that although we aim to have your advance transferred to you immediately, it can take up to 24 hours to clear in your bank account.
  
 Is it possible to lose access to my advance once I am a member?
 You will always have access to your advance(s) on-demand as long as your payments are made on time and your direct debit is connected. You can lose access to your advance(s) with Creditspring if you do not keep to the terms of the credit agreement.
 Please note that we may also terminate your membership and stop you from borrowing if:
 You don't inform us immediately when you give or receive proper notice of termination of your employment, if your income reduces, or there is any other material negative change in your financial circumstances
 If you fail to pay any monthly payment on its due date
 If any information you provide proves significantly incomplete or inaccurate
 If, without our consent, you cancel or do not complete a valid direct debit instruction.
 You can find a detailed account of these cases within the credit agreement.
  
 When can I request my second advance?
 You can access your second advance as soon as the first has been repaid in full and on time. You will not have to wait 14 days after repaying your first advance to request your second advance.
  
 What if I only use one advance during my 12-month credit agreement?
 As per your 12-month credit agreement with Creditspring, you have access to two on-demand advances. If your membership has ended and you haven't used your second advance, you will lose access to your second advance. If you sign up for a new membership, the terms from your new membership will only apply.

helpcentre_topic: I need more information > How do I make a complaint?
helpcentre_answers:
How to make a complaint
 You can make a complaint via the online form, by phone, or by post. All channels will be free of charge, or just cost you the normal rate voice or data allowance, or postage that you would otherwise generally pay. We will never charge anyone to make a complaint. Tell us what happened in as much detail as you can.
 If you'd like to get in touch with a general question or another issue then please click here or for an account-specific/payment issue then please click here.
 To make an official complaint via the online form please click here.
  
 When we've received your complaint
 If you make a complaint electronically, we'll automatically log your complaint into our complaints register. You'll get an email to let you know that's happened, and somebody from the Creditspring team will look into it. If you put your complaint in a letter, or make a complaint via the telephone, we will send you a receipt of your complaint via email.
  
 Getting to the bottom of the problem
 When we receive your complaint, we'll do our best to investigate it quickly and fairly. We'll try to find out what the problem was, and see if we're at fault. We'll also see what can be done to resolve your complaint. Please allow us up to two working days to investigate your complaint, or for us to request more time.
 If your complaint is especially serious, or demands the attention of a senior member of the team, we'll involve them as soon as possible.
  
 Making things right
 In all cases, we'll respond to your compliant via e-mail. For minor issues, we will send you an email letting you know we've looked into the problem and let you know of any improvements we intend to make.
 For something more serious (a complaint related to your membership or your loans, for example), somebody from the Creditspring team will reach out to you personally to explain how we're addressing your complaint.
 For the most severe type of complaints, somebody from the Creditspring team will immediately notify the company directors. A committee is formed to work out what went wrong, and to decide what the next steps should be. Once a solution has been found, a senior member of the Creditspring team will reach out to you, and a suggestion as to what should happen next.
 In some cases, we might receive a complaint due to the actions of a third party. If this is the case, we'll let you know in our response, with information on how to raise a complaint with them.
 If we resolve your complaint within three days, we will send you a Summary Resolution Communication. If it takes us longer than that to resolve your complaint, we will send you a Final Response. In both instances, we will inform you of your right to refer your complaint to the Financial Ombudsman Service (FOS) if you are dissatisfied with the way we handled your complaint.
  
 Escalation & dispute resolution
 If, after we have marked your complaint as resolved, you are not happy with the way we resolved your complaint, please let us know as soon as possible. We will conduct a new review and try to get it sorted.

I need more information > How do I make a complaint?How to make a complaint
 You can make a complaint via the online form, by phone, or by post. All channels will be free of charge, or just cost you the normal rate voice or data allowance, or postage that you would otherwise generally pay. We will never charge anyone to make a complaint. Tell us what happened in as much detail as you can.
 If you'd like to get in touch with a general question or another issue then please click here or for an account-specific/payment issue then please click here.
 To make an official complaint via the online form please click here.
  
 When we've received your complaint
 If you make a complaint electronically, we'll automatically log your complaint into our complaints register. You'll get an email to let you know that's happened, and somebody from the Creditspring team will look into it. If you put your complaint in a letter, or make a complaint via the telephone, we will send you a receipt of your complaint via email.
  
 Getting to the bottom of the problem
 When we receive your complaint, we'll do our best to investigate it quickly and fairly. We'll try to find out what the problem was, and see if we're at fault. We'll also see what can be done to resolve your complaint. Please allow us up to two working days to investigate your complaint, or for us to request more time.
 If your complaint is especially serious, or demands the attention of a senior member of the team, we'll involve them as soon as possible.
  
 Making things right
 In all cases, we'll respond to your compliant via e-mail. For minor issues, we will send you an email letting you know we've looked into the problem and let you know of any improvements we intend to make.
 For something more serious (a complaint related to your membership or your loans, for example), somebody from the Creditspring team will reach out to you personally to explain how we're addressing your complaint.
 For the most severe type of complaints, somebody from the Creditspring team will immediately notify the company directors. A committee is formed to work out what went wrong, and to decide what the next steps should be. Once a solution has been found, a senior member of the Creditspring team will reach out to you, and a suggestion as to what should happen next.
 In some cases, we might receive a complaint due to the actions of a third party. If this is the case, we'll let you know in our response, with information on how to raise a complaint with them.
 If we resolve your complaint within three days, we will send you a Summary Resolution Communication. If it takes us longer than that to resolve your complaint, we will send you a Final Response. helpcentre_topic: I need more information > When can I borrow?
helpcentre_answers:
Once approved, how long do I have to wait to access my advance?
 Once you are approved for a Creditspring Membership you will not be able to access your first advance for 14 days. There is a 14-day wait period in place for your first advance because we want to ensure our members are building their financial stability. By taking the time to set a financial plan and by having a thought-out backup plan in place for emergencies, Creditspring is here to assist you.
 After the 14 days, you'll be able to ask for your first advance whenever you want and we will transfer the funds to the bank account we have on file. Please be aware that although we aim to have your advance transferred to you immediately, it can take up to 24 hours to go through.
  
 When can I request my second advance?
 You can access your second advance as soon as the first has been repaid in full as long as the terms of the credit agreement have been followed. You may then request your second loan whenever you like before the end of your membership. You will not have to wait 14 days after repaying your first advance to request your second advance.
  
 Can I request a third advance?
 As per your credit agreement, Creditspring Members are only able to borrow a maximum of two advances per agreement term. If you'd like to renew your membership please find details here. We've got to know our members and so we make it much easier for them to renew with us.
  
 Is it possible to lose access to my advance once I am a member?
 You will always have access to your advance(s) on-demand as long as your payments are made on time and your direct debit is connected. It is possible for you to lose access to your advance(s) with Creditspring for various reasons. It could be because you have an overdue balance resulting in a default on your repayments. Please note in this case we may also terminate your membership and stop you from borrowing if:
 You don't inform us immediately when you give or receive proper notice of termination of your employment, income reduces or there is any other material negative change in your financial circumstances
 You fail to pay any monthly payment on its due date
 If any information you provide proves significantly incomplete or inaccurate
 If without our consent, you cancel or do not complete a valid direct debit instruction.
 You can find a detailed account of these cases within your credit agreement.
  
 What if I only use one advance during my 12-month credit agreement?
 As per your 12-month credit agreement with Creditspring, you have access to two on-demand advances. If your membership has ended and you haven't used your second advance, you will lose access to your second advance. If you sign up for a new membership, the terms from your new membership will only apply.

helpcentre_topic: I want to discuss my payments > Why have I been informed that my account will be reported as in default?
helpcentre_answers:
If you have received a default notice please click here.
  
 Why have I been informed that my account will be reported as in default?
 If you have not made loan repayments for the past 3 months, you will receive a notice. The notice will state that if your overdue balance is not paid in full within 28 days, then your account will be marked as in default. Your account has not, at the time of the letter being sent, been reported as in default to the credit rating agencies, but it is important to pay within the 28 day period to avoid this.
  
 You can clear any overdue amount via debit card payment here. Unfortunately, we will not be able to accept credit card payments.
  
 Can I change my payments to make them more manageable?
 If you're struggling with repayments we can offer forbearance to change the terms of your repayment schedule (either by changing the repayment dates or amount per payment). These changes will be reported to the credit-rating agencies but the impact is much lower than not paying. You can request this here.
 Alternatively, if you need help with your debts we recommend StepChange. They are a leading debt advice charity in the UK that offer FREE advice! Their website is www.stepchange.org and they operate a freephone debt helpline  0800 138 1111. Please note that we will need to directly hear from them within this 28 day period, or else we will be obligated to report your account status as in default to the credit rating agencies.

helpcentre_topic: I want to discuss my payments > When will my membership payments start?
helpcentre_answers:
When will my membership payments start?
 The first membership fee payment is due the day after your 14 day wait period. You can change future payments, however the first membership payment date cannot be changed. You can view your repayment schedule through your online account. You have the statutory right to cancel your membership at no cost as long as it is within the 14 day wait period. Please note that due to the way direct debit payments work, the payment may already be processing when you request to cancel your account. If you have completed cancellation within the 14 day grace period, any membership fee debited will be automatically refunded to your account.

helpcentre_topic: I want to discuss my payments > Why have I been sent a default notice?
helpcentre_answers:
Why have I been sent a default notice?
 The Default Notice is served under Section 87(1) of the Consumer Credit Act 1974 if you fail to meet the conditions of your agreement. If you have cancelled a direct debit without our consent, you are in breach of the terms of your agreement.
 As per the terms of the credit agreement, customers make payment to Creditspring via direct debit. We do accept one-off payments from other sources but it is a part of the agreement with us to have an active direct debit for your repayment schedule.
 If you are unable to make a payment this month you can cancel the direct debit with us. Payments can be processed by the bank up to 2 working days before they are due so please do this as early as possible. If your scheduled direct debit payment fails, you can pay this via debit card through your online account. We provide a 7 day grace period for all payments, if you make the payment within this time frame then we won't report it as late.
  
 How to reinstate
 If you have a cancelled direct debit mandate please click here and follow the instructions to reinstate it.

helpcentre_topic: I want to discuss my payments > Why was I sent a Notice of Sum In Arrears?
helpcentre_answers:
What is a Notice of Sum In Arrears (a NOSIA)?
 We are required to send a Notice of Sum in Arrears under section 86B of the Consumer Credit Act 1974, to anybody who has been late on making two or more payments under our regulated credit agreement. You will also receive this notice every six months if you have altered your repayment plan. Please note that this is based on your original repayment plan with Creditspring.
 You can clear the overdue amount via debit card by logging into your Creditspring account here. Unfortunately, we will not be able to accept credit card payments.
 If you cannot make a payment towards your overdue balance right away, please contact us to schedule a repayment date that works for you. Please note that when setting up a payment you will be charged on the earliest charge date (usually between 3-4 business days).
  
 Can I change my payments to make them more manageable?
 If you're struggling with repayments we can offer forbearance to change the terms of your repayment schedule (either by changing the repayment dates or amount per payment). These changes will be reported to the credit rating agencies but the impact is much lower than not paying. Please complete this short survey if you'd like to discuss restructuring your repayments so that we can understand the circumstances you face and work together on a solution.
 If you have any further questions regarding this please get in touch with us here.

In line with the credit agreement, we reserve the right to terminate accounts based on the outcome of this review.
  
 My account has been under review for over three working days
 If your account has been under review for over three working days and you haven't had a discussion with anyone on the team then please get in touch with us here.

helpcentre_topic: I want to change my account details > What should I do if I'm entering into an agreement with a debt agency?
helpcentre_answers:
What should I do if I'm entering into an agreement with a debt agency?
 We are sorry to hear about the situation that you are facing. Such arrangements can take many years to recover from and the agencies providing them can charge a large amount of administrative cost. If you would like to arrange a reduced repayment plan with us instead you can do so by completing the survey here to help us understand the situation.
 If you are entering an IVA, DMP or other debt management plan then please request that the agency you are using contact Creditspring as soon as possible so that we can update your account.
 Until we receive formal communication from them, you will continue to receive automated alerts and notifications regarding your account. If you still need to get in touch with us please click here.

helpcentre_topic: I want to change my account details > How do I change my bank details?
helpcentre_answers:
How do I change my bank details?
 As a new member
 Please be aware that your first membership payment must be paid from the bank account that you applied with and the scheduled payment date cannot be changed.
  
 How do I update my bank details?
 You can update your bank details within the profile section of your account. We will receive confirmation from your bank (this usually takes 3-4 business days). If you have recently changed your bank account and all your direct debits have been automatically moved to a new bank account, please notify us as soon as possible so that we can update the details of the new bank account on our records.
 Please note that the bank account must be in your name and older than three months. We will be able to change the bank details subject to the bank account passing the bank verification checks.
 If your bank account change is unsuccessful and you have already made your first payment please get in touch making sure to attach a copy of a recent bank statement to prove ownership of the account.
